<div id="review_1743427817" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1743427817" />
    <a title="Jessica" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1528855-jessica"><img alt="Jessica" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1248466738p2/1528855.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1743427817?book_show_action=true">Jun 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jessica" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jessica" href="/user/show/1528855-jessica">Jessica</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1743427817" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12375564179000944733">You guys! Holy moly, this was an undertaking. I love long tales that keep me engrossed and reading and I usually don’t want them to end. But this one, by the time it ended, I was sort of glad. I am ready to get back into my reading groove and on to a different tale. If you choose to undertake this journey, recognize this is a marathon and not a sprint. <br/><br/>This book could’ve been a series of several books, as each characters tale is worthy of a book dedicated completely to their own story. Each sect</span>
  <span id="freeText12375564179000944733" style="display:none">You guys! Holy moly, this was an undertaking. I love long tales that keep me engrossed and reading and I usually don’t want them to end. But this one, by the time it ended, I was sort of glad. I am ready to get back into my reading groove and on to a different tale. If you choose to undertake this journey, recognize this is a marathon and not a sprint. <br /><br />This book could’ve been a series of several books, as each characters tale is worthy of a book dedicated completely to their own story. Each section plays on the relationship of the character(s) that came before in some way making this an interlinked saga surrounding the estate of Oxmoon and the generations both blessed and cursed to possess it. I almost feel the estate itself becomes a palpable entity all its own silently influencing the Godwin family and heirs through several generations. Those familiar with English history may see the parallels between the 20th century Godwins and the 14th century Plantagenet legacy. <br /><br />If you like to be engrossed with the same characters and setting for a lengthy saga, especially when set on centuries-old English estates, I think you would enjoy this book. The writing is well done, if a bit elaborate and yet I found that I couldn’t skim over any parts as each seemed to be inclusive and vital, like a wheel, to moving everything forward. <br /><br />This was my first read from this author. I have also added a couple more from her repertoire to my list for future reads. </span>
  <a data-text-id="12375564179000944733" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


