<div id="review_1205089417" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1205089417" />
    <a title="Kathryn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/40435270-kathryn"><img alt="Kathryn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1483142087p2/40435270.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1205089417?book_show_action=true">Mar 11, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kathryn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kathryn" href="/user/show/40435270-kathryn">Kathryn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/38821070-the-wheel-of-fortune">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1205089417" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12044053127616731771">I finished! Maybe this is the influence of the recent Olympics talking but I feel like I should get a medal.<br/><br/>First, the good:<br/>- I enjoyed the fact that the book was broken into six parts, each written from the point of view of a different character. Since most of the people in this family were terrible at communicating, this left plenty of room for misunderstandings and different interpretations of the same events. <br/>- Some of the characters had refreshing styles with vivid metaphors like &quot;Conor’s j</span>
  <span id="freeText12044053127616731771" style="display:none">I finished! Maybe this is the influence of the recent Olympics talking but I feel like I should get a medal.<br /><br />First, the good:<br />- I enjoyed the fact that the book was broken into six parts, each written from the point of view of a different character. Since most of the people in this family were terrible at communicating, this left plenty of room for misunderstandings and different interpretations of the same events. <br />- Some of the characters had refreshing styles with vivid metaphors like "Conor’s just a skeleton in the closet who periodically rattles his bones too loudly."<br /><br />And now the bad:<br />- After occasional forays into interesting directions, the characters would quickly retreat to whatever mental or verbal tics the author had assigned them. One character was obsessed with winning in all aspects of life, another with "Beauty, Truth, Art and Peace!", etc. Several key players shared an obsession with "drawing the line" (that phrase appears 98 times in the book) and "doing the done thing" (78 times). The book got too caught up in archetypes (e.g. the magician) for my tastes, leading its characters to do silly or implausible things. The author demonstrated some self awareness of this at times when the characters would talk about whether people were "acting in character" but that just made it more annoying to me.<br />- There's no way this book needed to be this long. One character does an excellent job of summarizing most of the book in a short chapter towards the end of the book. If the author had stripped the book of its repetitive melodrama and made it more plot-driven, I think that she would have been left with a much shorter (and I expect a much more compelling) book.<br /><br />I'm glad it's over. I am so freaking tired of reading about "the lost Oxmoon of our childhood" (22 times) and that damn song The Blue Danube (48 TIMES!!!!)</span>
  <a data-text-id="12044053127616731771" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


